900503-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money Fund Assets
   Plunge as Investors
   Seek Higher Yields
   ----
   By Georgette Jasen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   Money market mutual fund investors are starting to look
for higher yields elsewhere.
   Money fund assets fell $3.5 billion in the week ended
Tuesday, the largest drop in more than two years, excluding
end-of-year seasonal declines, according to IBC/Donoghue's
Money Fund Report. Total assets of the 426 taxable funds
tracked by the Holliston, Mass., newsletter were $378.1
billion, the lowest in 12 weeks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The drop was entirely attributable to individual
investors; assets of funds open only to institutions rose
$948.3 million.
   "Money fund investors are pretty sophisticated," said
Brenda Malizia Negus, the newsletter's editor. "They're
locking in higher yields elsewhere . . . in CDs or
Treasurys."
   Yields on taxable money funds declined in the latest week,
while yields on certificates of deposit and Treasury
securities rose. The average seven-day compound yield of the
funds declined to 7.96% from 7.99%. Compound yields assume
reinvestment of dividends.
   Meanwhile, the yield on a six-month T-bill sold at
Monday's auction rose to 8.49% from 8.35% the week before.
Six-month CDs sold by major brokerage houses are currently
yielding an average of 8.37%, according to Banxquote Money
Markets, a New York information service.
   Yields are even better for longer-term investments.
Treasury notes and bonds, for instance, are yielding more
than 9% on maturities of two years and longer. Some big banks
are offering more than 9% on five-year CDs of more than
$90,000.
   Some of the withdrawals from money funds also went to pay
income taxes and some went into bond mutual funds, said
Walter Frank, chief economist for Donoghue's.
   Until the past few weeks, money fund assets had been
increasing steadily, sometimes more than $1 billion a week.
The most recent big drop was $3.6 billion at the end of 1989,
which was attributed to normal end-of-year withdrawals.
Assets fell $3.7 billion at the end of 1988. Yields have
fallen more than 1.5 percentage point since peaking April
1989, after months of steady increases.
   Average maturity of the funds investments -- such things
as commercial paper (short-term corporate IOUs), bank CDs and
short-term Treasury securities -- remained at a relatively
long 44 days in the latest week. Longer maturities usually
are considered a sign that portfolio managers think rates are
falling because the longer maturities enable the managers to
retain comparatively high yields longer.
   The average maturity has been longer than 40 days for
several months. The range has been 29 to 53 days in recent
years.
   The average seven-day simple yield of the taxable funds
fell to 7.67% from 7.69%. The average 30-day simple yield
slipped to 7.68% from 7.69%, while the average 30-day
compound yield went to 7.98% from 7.99%.
   Assets of tax-free money funds also fell, although yields
rose. Assets of the 220 tax-exempt funds tracked by
Donoghue's fell $1.2 billion, to $75.4 billion. The average
seven-day compound yield of the tax-free funds rose to 5.79%
from 5.74%. That's equal to 8.04% for an investor in the 28%
tax bracket and to 8.64% for someone paying 33%. Tax-free
yields have moved in response to the supply of tax-exempt
securities in recent months, said Mr. Frank of Donoghue's.
   The average maturity of the tax-free funds shortened to 41
days from 43 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0111
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0111.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Eastman Kodak
   Earnings Fell 6%
   In First Quarter
   ----
   By James S. Hirsch
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   EK
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Eastman Kodak Co., showing the benefits of extensive cost
cutting, recorded a 6% drop in first-quarter net income,
better than analysts expected.
   Net fell to $199 million, or 61 cents a share, from $212
million, or 65 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales fell to
$4.11 billion from $4.21 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Rochester, N.Y.-based photographic, chemical and
pharmaceutical concern said it restated 1989 results to
reflect the company's conversion to a calendar year. Kodak's
fiscal year began Dec. 26, and its quarters weren't uniform.
The change increased 1989 first-quarter net three cents a
share.
   In Kodak's core photographic products division, domestic
sales fell 15%, but lower costs and higher film prices helped
boost operating earnings 50% to $219 million. Colby H.
Chandler, chairman and chief executive officer, who retires
this month, cautioned that the rate of earnings increase in
this division will moderate in the coming months.
   Mr. Chandler said, "Barring unexpected developments in the
economy, we believe the recovery forecast for Kodak will come
about and that this will become increasingly clear in
subsequent quarters."
   Kodak's results exceeded most analysts' expectations of 50
to 55 cents a share, but analysts said it's uncertain how
much the improvement in photographic products comes from
one-time cost-cutting benefits derived from a restructuring
program announced last year, as opposed to fundamental
improvements in operations.
   Yet, despite the better-than-expected results, some
analysts expressed disappointment with the 3.5% decline in
operating profit, as earnings fell in Kodak's
information-system, chemical and health divisions.
   "Even though the company's on track in terms of Wall
Street's earnings expectations, how can you be excited if
chemical profits are off 38% and information systems is off
20%?" asked David Nelson, an analyst at Shearson Lehman
Hutton. "That's not the stuff you write home about."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0110
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0110.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Mass Murder and a Mall's Negligence
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<LP>
   In regard to the April 4 editorial-page article "Was a
Mall to Blame for a Mass Murder?" by Prof. Lawrence W.
Sherman: As the lead attorney for the plaintiffs who won the
case against the owners and management of the Springfield
Mall, in the Philadelphia suburbs, I view Prof. Sherman's
article as a sour-grapes attempt to win from a sympathetic
"jury" of business people the case his team lost in the
Delaware County Courthouse in February.
   He says the jury ruled that Sylvia Seegrist's "crime was
the fault of the shopping mall." In fact, the jury found that
the mall and its security staff were "negligent" in failing
to take reasonable precautions that would have prevented the
Seegrist rampage. As a professor, he should know the
difference between the two.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Semantics aside, judge for yourself the facts of what
occurred at the Springfield Mall prior to and on Oct. 30,
1985, the day Sylvia Seegrist shot and killed three people
and seriously wounded seven others.
   As Prof. Sherman notes, Ms. Seegrist had been a nuisance
at the mall over a period of time. But after the mass murder
of 21 people at a McDonald's restaurant in San Ysidro,
Calif., in 1984, her behavior turned belligerent, she made
deaths threats on several occasions, donned battle fatigues
and combat boots, and acted "bizarrely." He also noted that
she had been committed to mental hospitals 12 times and that
during one such commitment she stabbed a hospital employee.
   What he didn't mention was that:
   -- Just two weeks before the shootings, Ms. Seegrist was
in the McDonald's at the Springfield Mall threatening to kill
people.
   -- No one on the mall's security staff ever bothered to
find out Ms. Seegrist's mental state or her police record.
   -- No one on the mall's security staff ever called the
local police to notify them of the threats Ms. Seegrist had
made. If they had, she probably would have been banned from
the mall and possibly recommitted. The local police knew she
was dangerous and the chief of police testified to that
effect at the trial.
   -- There was no notification from one security shift to
another of Ms. Seegrist's activities so that some security
people had no idea who she was or what she did. No photo had
ever been taken of her by security to identify her as a
problem person, something routinely done with anyone who
shoplifts a few dollars' worth of merchandise.
   -- There was virtually no training for the security staff,
whose main focus was on protecting the premises and property
of the mall tenants, not the customers' safety.
   -- One of the mall security staff saw Ms. Seegrist,
dressed in battle gear, take a rifle from the back of her car
in the parking lot that fateful day, but took no action
because it was the day before Halloween and he thought it was
a prank.
   -- Security never called Ms. Seegrist's mother and told
her of her daughter's behavior. If it had, she would have
taken steps to keep Ms. Seegrist out of the mall because she
knew she was dangerous. She had been struck by her daughter
on more than one occasion.
   -- One forensic psychiatrist testified at the trial that
Ms. Seegrist picked the Springfield Mall not by coincidence,
but because she felt "comfortable" there. Why? Because she
tested the limits of what the mall would let her get away
with and found there were no serious limits on her outrageous
behavior.
   In his article, Prof. Sherman said "foreseeability" was a
"crucial legal question" in this case. He reasoned that if
the mall's security staff could not foresee what happened
that day, the mall should not be held negligent and liable.
To prove his point, he cited statistics that the odds on what
happened in the Springfield Mall were "1 in 156 million" and
the "prior rate of such crimes by women nationwide was zero."
   Now it's all well and good to cite probability in a
courtroom, but can you imagine a $3.75-an-hour security guard
stopping and computing the odds on mass murder when he
encounters a person making terroristic threats? Of course
not. But one can reasonably expect a security guard
confronted by someone in battle gear holding a rifle to stop
that person, and say, "Pardon me, but guns are not allowed in
the mall." And then to call the appropriate authorities.
   The reality is that an underpaid, poorly trained security
staff at the Springfield Mall did not take "reasonable care"
as is specified by Pennsylvania law for public places, i.e.
to exercise reasonable care to discover that intentionally
harmful acts of third persons are being done or are likely to
be done and to give warning to enable visitors to avoid the
harm or to protect them against it.
   Is it any wonder the jury took less than three hours to
find the Springfield Mall and its management guilty of
negligence?
   Rodger L. Mutzel
   Partner
   Cherry Ferrara Mutzel Belefonte McFadden &amp; Wesner
   Media, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0109
</DOCNO>
