<HL>
   Salomon Chief Tells
   Meeting His Views
   On `Liar's Poker'
   ---
   Gutfreund Says Book on Firm
   Caused Tension but Bears
   `No Relation to Reality'
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   SB
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- At Salomon Inc.'s annual meeting yesterday, it
was business as usual until somebody mentioned That Book.
   In an unusual diversion from Wall Street solemnity,
Salomon Chairman John Gutfreund treated shareholders to his
first comments on the book "Liar's Poker," a bestseller about
bond trading at the firm.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We have been a laughingstock" because of the book, he
said. The book apparently caused tensions with some clients.
But "we have overcome that by doing our job well."
   The bestselling book chronicles the bawdy antics of some
Salomon traders, including one known as the "Human Piranha."
Written by a former Salomon bond salesman, Michael Lewis, it
paints an unflattering picture of Salomon sticking certain
clients with bad bonds on occasion, among other things.
   At the meeting, Mr. Gutfreund said he never met the author
Mr. Lewis, and said the book bears "no relation to reality."
The book "systematically attempted to say we ravaged our
customers. It didn't make much sense," he said. "We may have
been stupid, but we have been honorable in dealing with our
customers."
   When "Liar's Poker" came out last autumn, Salomon
officials discussed the book at a morning meeting, telling
employees to read it so they'd be able to defend themselves,
industry executives said. Since then, the firm hasn't said
much publicly about the matter.
   But "Liar's Poker" wasn't the only piece of literature on
Salomon's agenda at yesterday's 1 1/4-hour meeting. Mr.
Gutfreund called "Barbarians at the Gate" -- the book about
the mammoth RJR Nabisco Inc. takeover -- a "pretty good
book."
   One passage in Barbarians has Salomon pulling out of the
deal because its name wouldn't be on the preferred side of a
planned advertisement. That passage was "a gross
oversimplification," Mr. Gutfreund said. "We had major
reservations about other aspects of the deal."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Southern Co.'s Net
   Slumped by 43%
   In First Quarter
   ----
   By Rick Christie
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   SO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Southern Co. reported its first-quarter earnings plunged
43% to $113.1 million, or 36 cents a share, because of higher
operating costs and sagging electricity sales.
   The drop marks the third consecutive quarterly earnings
decline for the operator of energy utilities in the
Southeast. In the 1989 first quarter, Atlanta-based Southern
earned $197 million, or 62 cents a share. Revenue slipped to
$1.67 billion in the most recent quarter from $1.68 billion a
year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The earnings slump comes at a time when the beleaguered
company faces new federal inquiries into alleged business
ties between Southern and the son of the company's chief
executive officer, Edward L. Addison, as well as a continuing
federal tax investigation into the company's accounting for
spare parts.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, Southern
closed at $23.625, down 50 cents.
   In recent quarters, Southern has been smarting from its
Georgia Power Co. unit's continuing rate dispute with the
Georgia Public Service Commission over the utility's Vogtle
nuclear-power plant. The commission has allowed Georgia Power
to recover only $218 million -- over a 10-year phase-in
period -- of the company's estimated $413 million in cost
overruns at the plant's No. 2 unit alone.
   Meanwhile, the latest quarter shows Southern carrying the
higher fixed costs for that unit, as well as the No. 4 unit
of its Scherer nuclear plant near Macon, Ga. "This was a
significant factor in our cost increases," a company
spokesman said. "Not only were we not carrying them last
year, but we've not received the rates to fully recover the
costs." The spokesman didn't specify the amount of the cost
increase.
   To make matters worse, Southern's kilowatt-hour sales fell
1.2% in the first quarter because of mild winter
temperatures, which affected the entire industry. The trend
apparently carried over through April, according to the
spokesman, which could hurt second-quarter earnings.
   The second-quarter results could be further affected by a
Mississippi Supreme Court ruling in April that the state's
four-year-old Performance Evaluation Plan is invalid.
Southern said the plan allowed residential electricity rates
for its Mississippi Power Co. unit to be automatically
adjusted according to its financial condition and
performance.
   But if the court's decision to curtail the plan as of
April 30 stands, Mississippi Power may have to refund as much
as $75 million to customers.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   A SOUTHERN CO. REQUEST to the Georgia Public Service
Commission for a $413 million rate increase was made to
recover the company's investment in the No. 2 unit of its
Vogtle nuclear power plant, as well as other costs of
providing services. In earlier editions it was misstated that
the $413 million was for cost overruns at the plant.
   (WSJ May 4, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
