<HL>
   GM Units Post
   Combined Drop
   In Quarter's Net
   ----
   By Jacqueline Mitchell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   GM GME GMH
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp.'s finance arm and
defense-related subsidiary reported lower first-quarter net
income, but its Electronic Data Systems Corp.
computer-services unit posted a 10% gain.
   All together, GM's three big non-automotive units posted
combined first-quarter profit of $591.4 million, down 6% from
a year earlier. The No. 1 auto maker is scheduled to report
first-quarter results for the rest of its operations,
including its core vehicle business, today.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At GM Hughes Electronics Corp., which includes the defense
operations of Hughes Aircraft Co. and the automotive
electronics operations of Delco Electronics Corp.,
first-quarter earnings slumped 16% to $145.6 million, or 46
cents a Class H share, from $172.9 million, or 51 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue fell 5.1% to $2.86 billion.
The unit blamed the declines on a combination of reduced
Pentagon spending and lower vehicle sales.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp., the auto maker's finance
arm, said first-quarter net income dropped 5.6% to $336
million from $356 million a year earlier. GMAC said its
year-earlier net reflected a onetime gain of $51 million from
the sale of GMAC's 51% interest in Isuzu Motors Finance Co.
to Isuzu Motors Ltd. However, the finance unit said it also
had a $48 million gain in the 1990 quarter, attributable to
changes in accounting practices related to certain European
operations.
   At Dallas-based Electronic Data Systems, meanwhile,
earnings rose 10% to $109.8 million, or 46 cents a Class E
share, from $100 million, or 41 cents a share. Revenue rose
10% to $1.42 billion. About 46% of EDS's first-quarter
revenue came from business outside GM. EDS has said its goal
is to have non-GM business equal revenue from the parent
company by the end of this year.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, GM
Class H stock, which represents dividend interest in GM
Hughes Electronics earnings, closed at $22.25, down 12.5
cents. GM Class E stock, which is tied to EDS, closed at
$30.625, up 25 cents. GMAC doesn't have a separately traded
stock; its profit contributes to the earnings for GM's common
stock.
   GM common closed at $44.75, up 50 cents.
</TEXT>
