<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Mexico's Progress
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   While Mikhail Gorbachev flounders with perestroika,
popularly elected Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
speeds forward with the reformation of Mexico's formerly
inert economy. Yesterday he submitted to the Mexican Congress
a bill to eliminate restrictions on private-sector ownership
of banks. Simply put, he plans to privatize Mexico's banking
system, nationalized in 1982 by former President Lopez
Portillo. To do so, Mr. Salinas will have to change the
constitution, and this takes a two-thirds vote by Congress.
But with the support of the free-market opposition party,
PAN, the President should be able to achieve this necessary
step in the continuing economic liberalization of Mexico.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0097
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0097.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   A Game of Chicken
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   The world's largest game of chicken ended this week, as
both Japan and the U.S. drove off the road before they rammed
each other in a trade collision. Unfortunately, Congress has
decreed that the same game be played every year, and one of
these times we may not be so lucky.
   A big trade crackup is just what many in Congress have in
mind. After George Bush decided to lift Japan and Brazil from
the "Super 301" trade-offender list, the Members sped to ram
Japan even though it'd made multiple trade concessions the
past 15 months. "It's time we quit playing patsy with these
guys," declared Rep. Frank Horton, a heretofore obscure
Republican from New York. Richard Gephardt, the House
Majority Leader, said Congress may pass legislation to force
Mr. Bush to cite Japan again, because "at the very moment you
ought to be hitting the gas, we're hitting the brake."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   George Bush ignored these reckless drivers. He knows that
after Japan's Prime Minister Kaifu made public concessions on
last year's 301 list -- on wood products, supercomputers and
satellites -- another U.S. slap could well have toppled him.
Mr. Bush also knows that the same Americans who hail the
smallest concession by Moscow, an historic adversary,
denounce any agreement with Japan, a friend and ally. These
people will never be satisfied.
   Yet even the Bush Administration seems enamored of the 301
"tool," as trade rep Carla Hills calls it. The idea is that
somehow the trade "pressure" of 301 is responsible for
Japanese concessions. This is impossible to disprove, but
Japan's own domestic politics probably have much more to do
with it. Japanese consumers are awakening to their relatively
poor standard of living, enough so that even Japan's
Socialist Party exploited the consumer issue in last year's
elections. Mr. Kaifu's Liberal Democrats have scrambled to
catch up.
   U.S. diplomacy may be a useful echo, but the ultimatum
that 301 represents -- give in or we retaliate -- is
counterproductive. It feeds the resentment of mirror-image
mercantilists in both countries -- for example, "The Japan
That Can Say No" crowd. It makes compromises more difficult.
Worst of all, if both sides fail to back down and the U.S.
retaliates, everyone loses. Japan's markets won't be open to
any greater degree, and American consumers will pay higher
prices on whatever goods the U.S. decides to punish in
return. What price, trade machismo? Sensibly, the Bush
Administration hopes to make further progress in the Uruguay
round of world trade talks set to conclude later this year.
   As we've said before, the 301 game of chicken is a
political reaction to a non-problem, the trade deficit. Mr.
Gephardt this week asserted that "the $49 billion trade
deficit this year with Japan represents one million lost
American jobs." The U.S. economy will create tens of
thousands of new jobs this year and has created some 20
million over the years that the deficit was even larger. U.S.
exports to Japan doubled in four years to $44 billion in
1989. Who's your economist, Dick?
   The world economy desperately needs American leadership,
but the 301 game makes us no better than the other
mercantilists pandering to domestic producers. It's a global
crackup waiting to happen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0096
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0096.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Simon's Venture Sells a Major Stake
   In HonFed Bank, Hawaii's Biggest Thrift
   ----
   By Richard B. Schmitt
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<LP>
   William E. Simon's thrift venture sold a major stake in
HonFed Bank, Hawaii's largest thrift, marking an unusual vote
of confidence for the troubled industry from an unusual
source.
   The investor, the Kamehameha Schools/Bishop Estate, a
wealthy Hawaiian educational trust and landowner, agreed to
invest $50 million in HonFed, which has assets of $3.2
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Simon, Treasury Secretary from 1974 to 1977, and his
partners paid $17 million to acquire control of the
institution in 1986 as part of a government-supervised
transaction.
   HonFed has been profitable recently, but, like hundreds of
thrifts around the country, it has been scrambling to raise
funds to comply with new federal capital requirements.
   At Dec. 31, HonFed had an estimated $24.5 million tangible
capital deficit and needed about $72 million in new funds to
meet federal regulations. The infusion is significant because
it is believed to be the first successful capital-raising
effort by an ongoing thrift since the new capital rules went
into effect in December.
   Still, the participation of what is commonly referred to
as the Bishop Estate, established in 1884 by the last
descendant of Hawaii's 19th century conquering King
Kamehameha I, is a two-edged sword for Mr. Simon and his
partners.
   On the one hand, the money combined with proceeds from
pending asset sales, may bring HonFed into compliance with
the key federal tangible capital test as soon as June 30,
when the now definitive agreement is expected to be
completed, officials said. That also is expected be an
impetus to HonFed's further growth, which has been
complicated lately by its lack of capital.
   On the other hand, the investment also will cut into the
Simon group's own return on equity investment in HonFed,
which last year reached a heady 47%. Terms of the Bishop
Estate investment weren't disclosed, although officials said
that the new equity investors won't have any voting rights.
   The $50 million infusion and planned asset sales also
replace a highly touted $100 million public preferred stock
offering that HonFed proposed last fall and that officials
said they would cancel. Some observers considered that
development somewhat embarrassing to Mr. Simon and his
investment bankers for the proposed offering, Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   Following his service at the Treasury, Mr. Simon became
something of a Wall Street darling, amassing an estimated
$200 million fortune from well-timed leveraged buy-outs of
such concerns as Gibson Greeting Cards and other ventures.
   Bert Ely, an Alexandria, Va., thrift analyst, said he
figures that the terms of a private transaction such as that
with Bishop Estate were less favorable to the Simon group
than under a public offering. Nonetheless, he said that such
private transactions probably would become the last best hope
for capital-shy thrifts because of continuing public jitters
about the sick industry.
   "We believed that this transaction could be done more
efficiently and with a very strong local partner that we
knew," said Gerald Parsky, a Los Angeles lawyer and a partner
in Mr. Simon's WSGP International, the Los Angeles-based
merchant bank that serves as the parent company for the
group's myriad financial ventures.
   The Bishop Estate, for instance, invested in the Simon
group's recent purchase and sale of First Interstate Bank of
Hawaii, a transaction that allowed participants to pocket an
estimated $20 million profit on a one-year investment of
about $15 million.
   In a statement, the estate's trustees called its latest
venture "an excellent investment opportunity with attractive
return potential." The Bishop Estate oversees a private
school for students of Hawaiian ancestry and is the islands'
largest private landowner with about 338,000 acres, equal to
about 8% of the state.
   Mr. Simon couldn't be reached for comment.
   HonFed reported 1989 profit of $8 million, down from $10.2
million in 1988, although fourth-quarter earnings rose to
$3.3 million from $1.2 million a year earlier. The
institution has about doubled in size since the Simon group
bought in, although last month it chose not to proceed with a
planned acquisition of 18 Hawaiian branches from First
Nationwide Bank because of capital concerns.
   HonFed is just one of three major thrifts that the Simon
group controls, and from a capital position, has been the
worst off. The others include Western Federal Saving &amp; Loan
Association of Marina Del Rey, Calif., and Southern
California Savings &amp; Loan Association, Beverly Hills.
   The $4.8 billion-asset Western Federal is generally
healthy; Southern California Savings, with about $2.3 billion
in assets, needs to raise about $35 million. Mr. Parsky said
Southern California Savings should be in compliance late next
year.
   Despite thrift assets currently totaling $10.5 billion,
the Simon group has been relatively quiet on the
thrift-acquisition front in recent months. Some officials
said the group remains committed to expanding itself,
however, and sees increasing opportunities as the government
steps up sales of insolvent thrifts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0095
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0095.
</DOCID>
