<HL>
   Technology:
   Johnson &amp; Johnson
   Unit's Hepatitis C Kit
   Is Approved by FDA
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<CO>
   JNJ CHIR
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Food and Drug Administration approved a
hepatitis C test kit developed by Ortho Diagnostics Systems
Inc., a unit of Johnson &amp; Johnson.
   The kit, which is used to detect hepatitis C in blood for
transfusions, includes a biotechnologically derived
recombinant antigen developed by Chiron Corp. of Ermeyville,
Calif. Chiron, whose stock is traded over the counter, has
licensed the product to Ortho.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The antigen detects the presence of the antibody to
hepatitis C, which is "responsible for the majority of
post-transfusion hepatitis cases," according to an FDA
spokeswoman. There are 170,000 new infections of hepatitis C
each year.
   The FDA is recommending the new screening test to all
blood banks. A spokesman for Ortho said the company will
begin shipping the test kits immediately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
