<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ford Capital BV -- $400 million of notes, due May 15,
2002, priced as 9 7/8% securities at 99.463 to yield 9.952%.
The noncallable notes were priced at a spread of 86 basis
points above the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated double-A-2 by
Moody's Investors Service Inc. and double-A by Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters led
by First Boston Corp. Ford Capital BV is the Dutch finance
subsidiary of Ford Motor Co. The notes are guaranteed by Ford
Motor.
   ITT Corp. -- $150 million of notes, due May 9, 1991,
priced at par to yield 9.125%. The noncallable notes were
priced at a spread of 50 basis points above the bond
equivalent yield of the Treasury's one-year bill. Rated
single-A-2 by Moody's and single-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be
sold through underwriters led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   Federal Farm Credit Banks -- $125 million issue of bonds,
due May 23, 1994, priced initially at par to yield 9.44%, or
a spread of 31 basis points above the Treasury's four-year
note. The bonds, which are noncallable for two years, will be
reoffered at various prices through Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   Commercial Credit Corp. -- $100 million of step-down
floating rate notes, due Nov. 13, 1991, priced at par to
float initially at a spread of 30 basis points above the
Federal Reserve's double-A rated 30-day commercial paper
rate. The rate on the noncallable notes will be reset monthly
with the first coupon set occuring on May 8. As part of the
stepdown feature, the notes will begin to float at a spread
of 25 basis points above the Fed's double-A 30-day commercial
paper rate starting Nov. 14, 1990. The notes are known as
step-down notes because the spread at which the notes float
tightens over time. Rated Baa-1 by Moody's and single-A-minus
by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNCIPALS
                                                                                                       

   New York State Mortgage Agency -- $111.7 million bonds
were repriced by a Bear Stearns &amp; Co. group late Tuesday. The
issue consists of Series OO term bonds and Series PP term
bonds. The Series OO bonds, which are super-sinker term
bonds, are 7.90% securities, priced at par due in 2010 and
8.05% securities, priced at par due in 2011. The Series PP
bonds, which are taxable, are 10.37% securities priced at par
due in 2005 and 10.75% securities priced at par due in 2012.
The bonds have been rated double-A by by Moody's.
   Indiana Health Facilities Authority -- $70 million revenue
bonds, tentatively priced by a First Boston Corp. group. The
bonds, for Bartholomew County Hospital Project, were priced
to yield from 6.80% in 1994 to 7.85% in 2020. The issue has
been rated triple-A by S&amp;P and is Capital Guaranty insured.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Banque Nationale de Paris -- 10 billion yen of step-down
coupon bonds due June 5, 1996, priced at 101 7/8, via JP
Morgan Securities. In first year, coupon is 18%, in the
second, 10%, in the third and fourth year 4% and in the fifth
and six year 2.4%.
   National Bank of Hungary (Hungary) -- 200 million Deutsche
marks of 9 3/4% bonds due May 29, 1996, priced at par, via
Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank (DG Bank).
   World Bank (agency) -- $150 million (Canadian) of 13 1/4%
Eurobonds due May 31, 1995, priced at 101 5/8 to yield 13.28%
less fees, via IBJ International. Fees 1 3/4.
