<HL>
   Who's News:
   Saxton is Named
   Chief of General
   Housewares Corp.
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   GHW WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   General Housewares Corp. named Paul A. Saxton, the
51-year-old president and chief operating officer, to the
additional post of chief executive officer.
   He succeeds John H. Muller Jr., 65, who remains chairman.
The appointment, which was made after the annual meeting
yesterday, is effective July 1.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Muller formed the Stamford, Conn., company almost 23
years ago. He cedes the top operations post just as the firm
has closed the sale of its candle unit, substantially
completed its effort to focus on the high end of cookware and
cutlery, and announced plans to move its corporate office to
Terre Haute, Ind., near its main plant.
   Housewares is "a very difficult business, and I didn't
realize how much when I got in," Mr. Muller said.
Fluctuations in interest rates, changes in life styles, plus
competition from the U.S. and overseas created roller-coaster
results at General Housewares, and the stock price followed
suit.
   General Housewares' stock price, which through the 1980s
ranged from $7 a share to near $30, has only rarely cleared
$14 a share since late 1984. The shares were unchanged
yesterday at $11 in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading.
   Now the challenge of strengthening and stabilizing General
Housewares' results, through marketing the company's Chicago
Cutlery and Magnalite cookware brands, falls entirely to Mr.
Saxton.
   Mr. Saxton, a former English instructor, came to General
Housewares from Allegheny International Inc.'s Sunbeam
appliance unit, where he was vice president, sales and
marketing. In his 3 1/2 years at Sunbeam, Mr. Saxton said,
sales nearly doubled to $228 million, and in September 1987,
Mr. Muller hired him to light a fire under General
Housewares' cookware business. In August 1989, he was named
president and chief operating officer.
   When Mr. Saxton joined General Housewares, one problem he
identified was that the company offered too many products,
confusing the sales force and making inventory control
difficult. He pared back the product lines, and in so doing
"jettisoned some things near and dear to {Mr. Muller's}
heart," Mr. Saxton said.
   Mr. Saxton determined to get the company out of
mass-merchant, low-priced cookware. "The better place to be
was the high end, but I bet on it only so much," Mr. Muller
said. And Mr. Saxton brought the sales force in house,
replacing independent representatives.
   Mr. Saxton also has determined to move the company's
marketing efforts away from retail stores and more directly
to consumers. He notes that the retailing industry is in
financial turmoil, and he suggests that busy consumers are
increasingly likely to choose offerings from a catalog or
home-shopping television program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0069
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0069.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Corvus Systems Files
   Plan to Reorganize
   In Bankruptcy Court
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CRVSQ
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Corvus Systems Inc., which sought
federal bankruptcy court protection nearly two years ago,
said it filed a proposed plan of reorganization.
   Under the terms of the plan, filed in federal bankruptcy
court in San Jose, the company's unsecured creditors would
receive an immediate cash payment equal to 10% of their
allowed claims from Corvus's current cash. They would get
another cash payment equal to 10% of their allowed claims
within 12 months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Corvus also said the plan provides that unsecured
creditors may receive one share of Corvus stock for every $10
of their claims, or they may participate in a creditors'
fund. Under the fund, they might receive further cash
payments on their claims from the sale of certain Corvus
assets, which the company declined to identify. Corvus
shareholders will retain their stock, subject to a one-for-10
reverse split, the company added.
   Corvus, which makes equipment that allows computers to
communicate with one another, said at the time of its filing
in June 1988 that its cash position wouldn't allow it to
"move forward" without Chapter 11 protection. Under Chapter
11 of the Bankruptcy Code, the company is protected from
creditor lawsuits while it works out a plan to pay its debts.
At the time of its filing, Corvus listed total assets of
$11.5 million and total liabilities of $9.6 million, of which
$3.6 million were secured.
   Under the plan, Corvus said its largest shareholder, Berg
&amp; Berg Industrial Developers, which controls 1.45 million
shares, or 8% of Corvus's common stock outstanding, is owed
$3.2 million and as a secured creditor would be paid in full
over a sevenyear period. The firm added in the plan that it
intends to file a lawsuit to ask the bankruptcy court to
determine the extent and value of Berg &amp; Berg's interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0068
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0068.
</DOCID>
