</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0063.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Senate Budget Committee Backs Plan
   To Cut Federal Deficit by $43 Billion
   ----
   By David Wessel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Budget Committee rallied behind a
plan to reduce the federal deficit by $43 billion by spending
less on defense and domestic programs than either the House
or the White House has proposed.
   After weeks of bickering and back-room bargaining, Budget
Committee Chairman James Sasser (D., Tenn.) won support for a
$1.23 trillion fiscal 1991 spending plan from all 13
Democrats on the panel as well as from Iowa Republican Sen.
Charles Grassley.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sasser called the plan "the largest single
deficit-reduction package we have passed in more than a
decade," and said it demonstrates that Congress can come up
with a budget without first negotiating with President Bush.
It also demonstrates Sen. Sasser's horse-trading ability: To
assemble a majority on his divided committee, he proposed no
cuts in farm subsidies whatsoever.
   The senior Republican on the budget panel, Sen. Pete
Domenici of New Mexico, predicted flatly that Congress won't
adopt the tax increases or spending cuts outlined in Sen.
Sasser's plan except as part of a pact with Mr. Bush. "There
is no way to get from where we are to where we have to be"
without a so-called budget summit, he said.
   Sen. Sasser said he hopes to bring the budget to the floor
of the Senate within 10 days. There it is certain to run into
fire from those who would cut defense spending more and
domestic spending less, and from others, including
influential Sen. Sam Nunn (D., Ga.), who would cut defense
spending less.
   The committee's budget essentially embraces all the tax
increases in the president's budget -- and then some. It
calls for $13.9 billion in tax increases plus $6.2 billion in
unspecified user fees. The House has a similar tax number,
but only $1.4 billion in fees.
   For the Pentagon, the Senate plan calls for cutting $13
billion from projected outlays in fiscal 1991, which starts
Oct. 1. That's more than the $11.5 billion in the budget
narrowly approved in the House this week and far from the
$3.2 billion in cuts in President Bush's budget, a figure the
administration itself has all but abandoned.
   Sen. Nunn, chairman of the Armed Services Committee, is
recommending a $10 billion cut. He termed the budget
committee's spending cuts "deeper than I believe can be
justified by the changes in the threat" from abroad and said
they would require sharp cutbacks in troop levels. But Sen.
James Exon Jr. (D., Neb.), who described himself as Sen.
Nunn's "right-hand man," voted with Sen. Sasser yesterday and
said he will do so on the floor.
   The Budget Committee also backed a sharp, $30 billion
reduction from projected levels in defense spending authority
-- essentially the sum to be deposited in the Pentagon's
checkbook to be spent over several years. The committee backs
$285.6 billion in spending authority, compared with $283
billion in the House budget. Sen. Nunn is calling for $289
billion. The Bush budget proposes $306.9 billion.
   The Senate committee's plan would spend substantially less
on domestic programs than would the president's budget, which
Democrats have criticized harshly. It would cut $3.6 billion
from projected spending on nondefense discretionary programs,
a category that includes everything from foreign aid to
housing assistance, compared with cuts of only $200 million
in the Bush budget and an increase of $3.7 billion in the
House budget.
   Although the total is stated boldly in the plan, the
specific cuts aren't. When pressed, Sen. Sasser said the list
includes saving $300 million next year, and billions in the
future, by terminating a giant atom smasher called the
superconducting supercollider.
   "There are no gimmicks here," Sen. Sasser asserted.
"There's nothing up our sleeve."
   But Sen. Domenici noted that Sen. Sasser's plan shows
increased spending in almost every government function, and
then lumps the proposed cuts together in one big catch-all
category at the bottom. Calling the maneuver "ingenious,"
Sen. Domenici said, "Everyone can say . . . they voted to
increase something."
   The Senate committee's budget does call for spending more
on entitlement programs, such as Medicare and federal
retirement programs, than President Bush has proposed. While
Mr. Bush would pare $5.5 billion from projected Medicare
spending, the committee would cut $2 billion and the House
$1.6 billion.
   If the Senate backs the Budget Committee's proposal, then
the two houses of Congress will attempt to reconcile their
differences to come up with a guide for appropriations and
tax-writing committees -- unless talks with the White House
begin first.
   In addition to the $43 billion deficit-reduction plan, the
Senate Budget Committee resolution calls for raising $11.1
billion by waiving penalties for Americans who pay their back
taxes and by intensifying tax-collection efforts. Sen. Sasser
included the amnesty scheme to win support from its author,
Sen. Kent Conrad (D., N.D.), and from Sen. Charles Robb (D.,
Va.), who added the figures together and said he was voting
for a $54.1 billion plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0062
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0062.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Speaking of Business:
   Japan Doesn't Always Do Everything Right
   ----
   By Lindley H. Clark Jr.
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   The U.S. is Japan's best customer, so it's not surprising
that the Japanese for many years avoided overt criticism of
Uncle Sam. But the Oriental patience gradually eroded and, in
the past year or so, there have been books, articles and
public proclamations from Tokyo that the U.S. should stop
blaming Japan for its trouble and clean up its own house.
   These criticisms have gotten farther than they might have
in chauvinistic America because Americans have begun to feel
that the Japanese do almost everything right. New ideas may
come from the U.S. but Japan knows how to convert them into
profitable products. At the time we were becoming accustomed
to 4% to 5% inflation, which would double prices in 15 years
or so, Japan was trudging along with price increases
averaging 1% or so.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Suddenly it has become apparent that the Japanese are
human beings after all. By the end of 1987, after a great
deal of manipulation by the U.S., Japan and other nations,
the dollar had plunged to 120 yen. A strong currency is often
viewed as an indicator of a strong economy, but Japan didn't
like this situation. Either Americans would have to be
persuaded to pay more for Toyotas and Hondas or they would
buy fewer of them -- or Japan would have to cut its prices to
keep market share.
   Japan mainly opted to cut prices, so profits declined.
Japan also decided to weaken the yen in the standard way: by
inflating the economy. The solution worked the way any
Economics 101 student would tell you it would work. The yen
has dropped and may go lower. Japan, whose wholesale prices
dropped every year from 1984 through 1988, has had
substantial price increases since then.
   The inflation has been most spectacular in land. Milton
Friedman, the Nobel economist, talking to Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
clients earlier this year, noted that the value of the land
in Tokyo is now equal to the value of all the land in the
U.S. In 1946, Bank of America bought a house for the manager
of its Tokyo branch, paying about $40,000. Recently the bank,
looking around for assets to sell, found that the house was
now worth $40 million -- and sold it.
   Japan may not allow its inflation to get out of hand. The
Bank of Japan has had a change in management, and the new
people seem determined to keep prices in check. At any rate,
despite predictable political objections, the bank has been
maneuvering increases in interest rates.
   Higher interest rates aren't welcome in a country that has
grown on the basis of cheap credit. But at least some
Japanese seem to recognize that this is something they have
done to themselves, not a punishment inflicted by foreigners.
   Since fooling around with exchange rates was the main
cause of Japan's troubles, it might be hoped that the
Japanese in the future will forgo such foolishness. But
that's a lot to hope. The U.S. still fools around with
exchange rates, although the effectiveness of such actions is
at least controversial. The U.S. "sterilizes" its
intervention, offsetting inflationary effects by buying or
selling securities in the domestic market.
   To the extent that there is a significant effect, it's
probably more psychological than real. If the intervention
doesn't achieve its aim, the market knows the U.S. government
probably will try again, silly as such action may be. Anyway,
the market isn't likely to try to thwart what it perceives as
the government's wishes.
   Several people recently, however, have questioned whether
the U.S. is playing this game by the rules -- its own rules,
that is. Anna J. Schwartz, in a paper for the Shadow Open
Market Committee in March, noted that Congress in 1934
empowered the Treasury to deal in foreign currencies to
"stabilize" exchange rates.
   Most of the funds the Treasury was given were taken over
by the International Monetary Fund after World War II. That
left the Treasury with limited sums to play around with, so
the Treasury enlisted the Federal Reserve as a player.
   The legal basis for the Fed's participation is at best
questionable. A number of Fed officials aren't happy about
it, but the game goes on. The Federal Reserve now
"warehouses" foreign currencies for the Treasury, in effect
making no-interest loans to the Treasury. At best this
operation distracts Fed officials from their own problems,
such as persistent U.S. inflation.
   Even if this operation is necessary, Mrs. Schwartz argues
that the Treasury and the Fed should at least ask Congress
for authority. But the Fed, which has the unique ability to
create its own money, simply goes on helping the Treasury
out.
   So both the U.S. and Japan are having trouble getting
their acts together. In the circumstances it seems wise that
the Bush administration has decided not to condemn Japan this
year under the so-called Super 301 provision of the trade
law. The failure to include Japan this time didn't attract
many complaints from Congress, so maybe this punitive law is
losing some of its support. Maybe American politicians are
learning.
   Maybe Japanese politicians are learning, too. They are
concerned about inflation, and they are taking some steps to
open their markets; maybe they're learning that more
competition tends to hold down prices.
   Japan, it's apparent, has done some things wrong. It's in
our interest, and theirs, for both of us to stop
finger-pointing and deal with our own problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900503-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900503-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Bond Prices Little Changed in Lifeless Trading;
   No Surprises in Terms for Treasury Refunding
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Andrew Bary
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   F ADD MZ EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bond prices ended little changed in lifeless
trading activity as investors anxiously awaited details of
the Treasury's next big bond auction.
   The announcement, which came very late in the day, had
little impact on the market because the terms of the auction
were as analysts had expected. The Treasury said it will sell
a record $30.5 billion of notes and bonds at next week's
quarterly refunding of the federal debt. The government will
auction $10.5 billion of three-year notes Tuesday, $10
billion of 10-year notes Wednesday and $10 billion of 30-year
bonds next Thursday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury also set the next auction for Resolution
Funding Corp. thrift bailout bonds for July 10 and said it
will announce details of the auction July 3.
   In trading yesterday, Treasury bond prices initially fell
as much as 3/8 point, or $3.75 for a bond with a $1,000 face
amount, following news that Federal Reserve Board Vice
Chairman Manuel Johnson said inflation was too high.
   But Treasury prices recuperated later to end unchanged to
about 1/8 point higher.
   Mr. Johnson's remarks, which were made to reporters after
a speech to executives of the National Automated Clearing
House Association, were interpreted by investors as yet
another sign that the Fed may eventually raise interest rates
in an effort to reduce inflationary pressures.
   The comments were especially disturbing considering that
the date of the Fed's Federal Open Market Committee meeting
is fast approaching. The committee, which is the Fed's
policy-making arm, will meet on May 15, and the members will
decide whether to change monetary policy.
   Fears of Fed tightening seemed to have calmed down a bit
later in the day when the Fed released the latest edition of
its so-called beige book, a summary of economic conditions
prepared for use by policymakers before their May 15 meeting
in Washington.
   The report indicated that economic activity continues to
expand slowly across the country, but not fast enough to
allow the Fed room to raise interest rates. Manufacturing,
which has been depressed in many parts of the nation, is
improving.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   The mortgage securities market was abuzz with talk that
the Comptroller of the Currency may soon impose curbs on
commercial banks' holdings of certain high-yielding mortgage
securities.
   Banks have been big buyers of all mortgage securities
during the past year because new risk-based capital bank
standards favor these securities over many traditional bank
investments.
   But dealers on Wall Street said the comptroller's office
is concerned with the large increase in bank holdings of
derivative securities, which are a riskier type of mortgage
security. These would include highly volatile securities such
as inverse floating-rate, zero-coupon, residual and "jump Z"
bonds. The comptroller might also restrict "companion" bonds
with original average lives of more than seven years.
Companion bonds are relatively high-yielding derivative
securities that are created in tandem with
prepayment-protected planned amortization classes.
   A spokesman for the comptroller said regulations on bank
investment in mortgage securities are "in the formulation
stage," but nothing has been made final.
   Andrew Carron, head of mortgage research at First Boston
Corp., said banks would probably be permitted to hold most
standard derivative mortgage securities. These would include
"plain vanilla" real estate mortgage investment conduits,
which are a type of collateralized mortgage obligation.
   In trading yesterday, most mortgage-backed securities
ended little changed.
                                                                                                       

   Corporate Issues
                                                                                                       

   Ford Capital BV, the Dutch-based finance subsidiary of
Ford Motor Co., made its debut in the U.S. credit markets
with $400 million of 12-year notes. The notes were priced to
yield 9.952%.
   Ford Capital is a financing vehicle set up primarily to
refinance debt incurred in connection with Ford Motor's $2.52
billion acquisition of Jaguar PLC.
   It is unusual for offshore units of U.S. companies to tap
the U.S. debt market because their primary purpose is to
raise capital through the Eurobond market.
   But Peter Milhaupt, director of capital markets at lead
underwriter First Boston Corp., said the U.S. market is
currently more attractive than the Euromarket for domestic
issuers.
   Among other things, Mr. Milhaupt noted that European rates
have been rising relative to U.S. rates and that traditional
Eurobond investors tend to prefer securities that mature in
10 years or less.
   Moreover, he said, "The Euromarket has not been able to
consistently" absorb certain types of bond offerings. "It is
our judgment that for the size, $400 million, and the
maturity, 12 years, {Ford} could not get this kind of
execution in that market in Eurodollars or for that matter by
swapping out of currencies" for dollars, said Mr. Milhaupt.
   Although First Boston officials said the deal went well
and attracted a broad-based buying interest from
institutional investors, some corporate bond traders said the
issue was priced a little aggressively.
   The non-callable notes were priced at a spread of 0.86
percentage point above the Treasury's 10-year note. A
comparable Ford Holdings 9 1/4% issue of 10-year notes is
trading at 0.89 percentage point above the Treasury's 10-year
note, dealers said. Officials at First Boston said the deal
hasn't been completely sold yet.
                                                                                                       

   Junk Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Broad buying interest buoyed the junk bond market, lifting
prices of most actively traded bonds.
   Most junk bonds, which are high-yield speculative-grade
securities with low credit ratings or no credit ratings,
gained 1/8 and 1/4 point.
   Meanwhile, Moody's Investors Service Inc. said junk bonds
were the best performing sector of the bond market last month
after being one of the worse performing sectors most of last
year.
   In its latest bond-market performance report, Moody's said
junk bonds eked out a small 0.5% total return last month.
While that's not a stellar performance, it's far better than
the minus 2% total return posted on long-term Treasury bonds
and the minus 1.5% total return on investment-grade corporate
bonds. Moody's said the biggest losers last month were
long-term zero-coupon Treasury bonds, which plunged 8% last
month.
   In trading yesterday, the junk bonds of Ames Department
Stores Inc. were again the major market-mover as vulture
funds and other investors in distressed securities continued
to swoop down and snap up the retailer's bonds.
   Ever since the Rocky Hill, Conn.-based firm filed for
protection under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code,
its bonds have been gaining ground. Some investors believe
the bonds will be valued at higher levels if and when the
company emerges from bankruptcy-law proceedings. Ames's 13%
senior subordinated reset notes, due in 1999, rose 2 1/4
points to end at 27 1/2.
   The junk bonds of R.H. Macy &amp; Co. were unchanged despite
news that the retailer has reduced its loss for the third
quarter. In a letter to investors, Macy said that despite
almost flat sales, it was able to reduce its loss for the
quarter ended April 28. In the year-earlier third quarter,
the company reported a loss of $64 million, on sales of $1.5
billion.
   Macy's 14 1/2% senior subordinated debentures, due in
1998, were unchanged at 70 1/2, while its 14 1/2%
subordinated debentures, maturing in 2001, were little
changed at 61.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   The benchmark 30-year bonds ended at 94 19/32 to yield
9.01%, up from 94 14/32 to yield 9.03% on Tuesday. Two-year
notes ended unchanged at 99 23/32 to yield 8.997%.
   Short-term rates ended little changed. The discount rate
on three-month Treasury bills eased slightly to 7.90% for a
bond-equivalent yield of 8.152%, while the rate on six-month
bills was slightly lower at 8.02% for a bond-equivalent yield
of 8.464%.
                                                                                                       

   Municipals
                                                                                                       

   In a repeat performance of Tuesday's sleepy dealings,
municipal bonds finished narrowly mixed in fairly active
trading. Some actively traded issues were off as much as 1/4
point, while other issues were up as much as 1/8 point.
   Municipals aren't expected to show much life until the
path of the Treasury bond market is clearer, traders said.
   In light primary market activity, a First Boston Corp.
group priced $70 million of Indiana Health Facilities
Authority revenue bonds.
   In secondary market activity, New Jersey Turnpike
Authority's 7.20% issue of 2018 was unchanged at 95 bid to
yield 7.62%.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   News that East and West Germany agreed on terms of
monetary union had only a modest impact on the West German
bond market.
   Under terms of the agreement, most East Germans will be
able to convert 4,000 East German marks of savings into West
German marks at a 1-to-1 exchange rate. East Germans who are
60 years old and over will be able to convert 6,000 East
German marks at the favorable rate, while those 14 and
younger will be limited to 2,000 marks. Remaining savings
will be converted at a 2-to-1 rate. West Germany said the new
official exchange rates become effective immediately.
   Investors took the news surprisingly well, considering the
West German bond market has been depressed for months because
of fears that reunification of the two currencies would
result in exorbitant inflation, especially if the exchange
rate came in at 1 to 1.
   But analysts said inflation concerns already have been
priced into the market.
   In trading, West Germany's benchmark 7 3/4% bond due in
2000 fell 0.25 point to 92.95 to yield 8.85%.
</TEXT>
