<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   AMERICAN GENERAL surprised shareholders by putting itself
up for sale after saying it apparently had won a proxy fight
to maintain its independence. The big insurer said it is
worth "substantially" more than the $50 a share, or $6.3
billion, that Torchmark had offered in March. American
General soared $7.50 a share to $47.625 in Big Board trading.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court reversed the conviction of former
stockbroker Robert Chestman and ordered his release from
prison. The federal panel also gutted an SEC regulation that
is widely used in insider-trading cases.
   ---
   Leading economic indicators rose 0.9% in March, the
biggest increase since June 1988, suggesting the economy will
continue to grow moderately. Factory orders rose 3.8% in
March, as aircraft orders spurted.
   ---
   The Fed hasn't found much evidence of a large-scale credit
crunch, despite reports that banks were reluctant to make
loans to businesses.
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices advanced after the report, which also cited
modest economic growth. The Dow Jones industrials rose 20.72
points to 2689.64.
   ---
   The Treasury plans to sell a record $30.5 billion of notes
and bonds at next week's refunding of the federal debt,
partially to finance S&amp;L bailouts.
   ---
   OPEC postponed the start of an emergercy meeting in Geneva
after informal talks revealed disagreement over temporary oil
production cuts. Spot prices fell on the news.
   ---
   Mexico's banking system would be returned to private
control under a proposal announced by President Salinas. The
plan was hailed by businessmen as a boon to companies seeking
financing in Mexico.
   ---
   William Simon's thrift venture sold a major stake in
HonFed Bank to a Hawaiian educational trust for $50 million,
as part of its efforts to meet new federal capital
requirements.
   ---
   Henley Group plans to spin off its two largest units,
Fisher Scientific and Pneumo Abex, to shareholders in
tax-free distributions.
   ---
   The Senate budget panel rallied behind a plan to trim the
federal deficit by $43 billion by spending less on defense
and domestic programs than the House or White House wants.
   ---
   GM's finance arm posted lower first-quarter earnings, as
did its defense-related subsidiary. But its computer-services
unit had a 10% gain.
   ---
   Monsanto named Robert B. Shapiro, who established a
reputation as a marketing whiz at the firm's NutraSweet unit,
to head its big agricultural-products business.
   ---
   Japanese companies moved to collect export insurance on
delayed payments from Soviet importers.
   ---
   Southern Co.'s earnings fell 43% in the first quarter, the
third consecutive quarterly earnings decline for the
beleaguered utility operator.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 141,610,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2689.64, up 20.72; transportation 1138.69, up 1.78; utilities
204.79, up 0.69.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3222.93, up
1.34.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.74, up 0.25; spot
index 135.13, up 0.98.
   Dollar: 157.95 yen, off 0.88; 1.6848 marks, up 0.0040.
</TEXT>
