<HL>
   Northeast Savings
   Posts 4th-Period Loss
   On Big Write-Down
</HL>
<DATE>
05/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NSB
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   HARTFORD, Conn. -- Northeast Savings F.A. reported a net
loss of $106.9 million, or $19.07 a share, for the fourth
quarter ended March 31 because of a write-down of good will
but said operations are showing "solid progress."
   A year earlier, it reported net income of $2.1 million, or
a net loss of four cents a share, after payment of preferred
dividends.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Northeast said that before the $110.3 million write-down
of good will, net was $3.4 million, or 22 cents a share.
   George P. Rutland, chairman and president, said the good
will represented the value of having a unique two-state
thrift business in Connecticut and Massachusetts at a time
when interstate banking was restricted in the region. Due to
the passage of liberalized interstate banking laws, "that
franchise doesn't have the value it used to have," he said.
   After the write-down, Northeast still has $90 million in
good will on its books. It previously filed a suit
challenging the Federal Office of Thrift Supervision's
requirement that good will can't be counted toward meeting
regulatory requirements.
   Mr. Rutland said Northeast has been successfully reducing
its size. At the end of fiscal 1990, assets were $4.97
billion, down 37% from $7.94 billion a year earlier. While
retail deposits are down only 3% to $3.4 million, brokered
deposits are down 69% to $304.4 million.
   Mr. Rutland said that over the past year Northeast sold
off all but $16.1 million of its $314.1 million junk-bond
portfolio, taking a $13 million loss.
   For the year, Northeast reported a loss of $107.1 million,
or $20.27 a share, after writing down the good will. In
fiscal 1989, it had a loss of $12.9 million, or $4.40 a
share.
</TEXT>
